  - Feature engineering refinement
  - Hyperparameter tuning
  - Using more quality data

ğŸš€ NEXT STEPS FOR YOUR CODE
================================================================================
1. Import libraries: pandas, numpy, sklearn, matplotlib
2. Load student data (CSV file)
3. Explore data: visualize distributions, correlations
4. Preprocess: normalize, handle missing values
5. Split data: train/test split
6. Choose model: start with LogisticRegression
7. Train model: fit on training data
8. Make predictions: test on new data
9. Evaluate: calculate accuracy, precision, recall
10. Visualize results: confusion matrix, ROC curve
11. Save model: use joblib or pickle
12. Create prediction function: predict new students

ğŸ’» PSEUDOCODE STRUCTURE
================================================================================

# 1. IMPORT & LOAD DATA
import pandas, sklearn, numpy
data = load_student_data('students.csv')

# 2. PREPARE DATA
X = data[features]                    # Input features
y = data['result']                    # Output (PASS/FAIL)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split()

# 3. NORMALIZE
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# 4. CREATE & TRAIN MODEL
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# 5. PREDICT
predictions = model.predict(X_test)

# 6. EVALUATE
accuracy = calculate_accuracy(predictions, y_test)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}%")

# 7. PREDICT FOR NEW STUDENT
new_student = [85, 2.9, 15, 80, 70, 6, 1]
prediction = model.predict([new_student])
print(f"Result: {'PASS' if prediction[0] == 1 else 'FAIL'}")

